                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><strong>Erector Spinae</strong></h3><p>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">erector spinae</a> is a group of muscles that run along the back from the skull down to the pelvis. It consists of three muscles — the longissimus, iliocostalis, and spinalis. All three of these muscles work together to mobilize and stabilize the spine.</p><p>In a bird dog, the erector spinae is the primary muscle group worked. When we extend our arms and legs, the erector spinae muscles shorten and contract. This helps to maintain spinal stability while straightening the limbs. As you return to the starting position, they stretch and lengthen to prevent the spine from excessive arching or rounding.</p><p>Bird dogs provide a <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4853948/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">moderate muscle stimulus</a> to the erector spinae muscles. You can increase the muscle activation rate by adding more <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1016/j.pmrj.2016.05.017" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">intensity</a> to the exercise. This could be accomplished by increasing the time spent under tension or adding a resistance band.</p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
